/* Unidentified name */
SAY NAME1 ~War Hammer~
/* Identified name */
SAY NAME2 ~Sofn +5~

SAY UNIDENTIFIED_DESC
~Mounted knights cannot effectively use long pole weapons while on horseback, and as a result, many weapons have been fitted with shorter shafts so they may be wielded with just one hand.  Maces and flails are two previous examples of this - the war hammer is another.  The horseman's war hammer is a descendant of the Lucerne hammer.  It is made entirely of steel, with rondels protecting and strengthening the grip.  Rondels are small disks of metal, often shaped into decorative designs.  The shaft is about 18 inches long.

STATISTICS:

Damage:  1D4 + 1
Damage type:  crushing
Weight: 6
Speed Factor: 2
Proficiency Type: War Hammer
Type:  1-handed
Requires: 10 Strength
Not Usable By:
 Druid
 Mage
 Thief~

SAY DESC
~Sofn +5
Pvolmier was by DR1347 have become one of better known blacksmiths in his craft and so he captured attention of dwarwen noble Krustur who ordered a pair of weapons an one handed war hammer and throwing axe. Pvolmier have forged required axe and hammer quite fast but he had problems with sourcing enchanters who considered enhancing debilitating effects of crushing weapons impossible despite Pvolmier knowing it is doable and having accomplished such feat so he declared a public challenge. Krustur who ordered intended the weapons to be unremarkable as possible was unnerved by this challenge and canceled the order but on of his enemies a dwarven noble by the name of Varg has promised to supply an enchanter just to humiliate Krustur. Krustur also arrived but he came into blows and in resulting scuffle Varg killed Krustur with single blow. This is how Sofn came to existence. Chroniclers record that Varg was imprisoned after and had to sell the weapons or his family had sold the weapons but it doubtful they had fetched a very high price because Varg had insisted on placing enchantment that no non-dwarf can use this weapon.

STATISTICS:

Combat Abilities:
   33% chance with each successful attack that the target is slowed for three rounds (No Save)
   25% chance with each successful attack that the target is stunned for one round (No Save)
   5% chance with each successful attack that the target is rendered unconscious for one round (No Save)

THAC0: +5
Damage:  2D4 + 6
Damage type:  crushing
Weight: 2
Speed Factor: 2
Proficiency Type: War Hammer
Type:  1-handed
Requires: 10 Strength
Not Usable By:
 Non-Dwarves
 Bard
 Paladin
 Ranger
 Thief
 Monk
 Druid
 Mage
~

// Korolnor Berserker Pouch -------------------- 15
COPY ~grand_duke/itm/rqpotn60.itm~ ~override/rqpotn60.itm~
/* Unidentified name */
SAY NAME1 ~Pouch~
/* Identified name */
SAY NAME2 ~Korolnor Berserker Pouch~
SAY UNIDENTIFIED_DESC
~This small bag is ideally suited for holding gems.~
SAY DESC
~Korolnor Berserker Pouch
It is said that some dwarves from Korolnor used herbs contained in these bags to induce berserker rage. Scholars have records of flasks that were magical and could restore their enrage ability each day, but these flasks have probably not survived to this day. This bag is not magical and contains only a limited amount of content before it is fully drained.
The flask comes with some disadvantages: anyone who is not a dwarf will be unable to stomach the disgusting smell of the concoction, so its use is limited to dwarves. Even then, it is further restricted to only those dwarves with sufficiently high Constitution; otherwise, they would not be able to ingest this repulsive herbal mix.

Special abilities:
Consume one sip of the potion to enrage the user like a berserker would.

The enraged state lasts for 60 seconds:
- While enraged: +2 to hit, +2 damage, -2 AC
- While enraged: immune to Charm, Confusion, Fear, Feeblemind, Hold, Imprisonment, Level Drain, Maze, Stun, and Sleep
- While enraged: gains 15 hit points. These hit points are temporary and are taken away at the end of the berserk spree, possibly killing the berserker.
Requires: 18 Constitution

Not Usable By:
Non-dwarves
~

// Baalzebul's Rejuvenator ------------------------------ 19
COPY ~grand_duke/itm/rqtome02.itm~ ~override/rqtome02.itm~
/* Unidentified name */
SAY NAME1 ~Manual~
/* Identified name */
SAY NAME2 ~Baalzebul's Rejuvenator~

SAY UNIDENTIFIED_DESC
~Judging by the arcane symbols printed on its cover, it is clear that this book is imbued with magical properties of one sort or another. Until you attempt to either read or identify it, however, its precise nature will remain unknown to you.~

SAY DESC
~Baalzebul's Rejuvenation
This tome was originally created for one of Baalzebul's lieutenants, who demanded a magical item that could be used to heal his subordinates. A devilish enchanter assigned to the task handled it quite easily. However, when he sent the tome, it was intercepted by a scheming devil named Ischameel, who longed to have Baalzebul's personal enchanter replaced by one of his own. It is generally assumed that Ischameel sold the artifact in Faerun. Using the tome imprisons the user for three rounds in an Abyssal pocket. In this pocket plane, there is only one object: a large version of this exact tome. To receive healing, the user must write their name in the book, and the tome will then record further details about them and sometimes even quite disturbing details about their past. All previous users have heard a soft wailing when they are freed from imprisonment, which leads scholars to believe that the book transfers life force of some unfortunate soul from multiverse to the user. Therefore, no one with good or neutral alignment can bring themselves to use this tome.

Requires: 15 Constitution
Requires: 9 Intelligence
Requires: 9 Wisdom

STATISTICS::
Can move the user to an extra-dimensional space where they are fully healed, then return after three rounds. Usable three times per day.

Not Usable By:
  Good or Neutral alignment
~

// Charged Divination Gem ------------------------------ 12
COPY ~grand_duke/itm/rqgem02.itm~ ~override/rqgem02.itm~
/* Unidentified name */
SAY NAME1 ~Emerald~
/* Identified name */
SAY NAME2 ~Lesser Divining Gem DIl & DIn & Cl~

SAY UNIDENTIFIED_DESC
~Tourmaline is a versatile, semi-transparent gemstone known for its wide range of vibrant colors, including striking blue varieties like indicolite, with a glass-like luster and good durability. Its unique crystal structure and range of hues make it a popular choice for jewelry.~

SAY DESC
~Lesser Divining Gem DIl & DIn & Cl
Less powerful than the Greater Gem of Seeing, this gem was originally enchanted for bard Athelmas, whose frequent travels led him to complain to his friend, enchanter Myrtlym. When they met, Myrtlym gave Athelmas this very gem. Chroniclers agree that the next owner was necromancer Launner, who probably killed Athelmas for the gem, sensing its powerful divination magic. The last owner recorded by chroniclers was ogre mage Bolad. Some scholars strongly dispute the fanciful tale about Myrtlym and Athelmas and point to the standard size of tourmalines compared to other charged divination gems, as well as markings indicating which spells could be cast. All of which suggests an old, forgotten manufacturing guild which specialized in the production of charged divination gems.

This gem bears inscriptions of the letters DIl, DIn, and Cl, which indicate the spells that can be cast. When fully charged, the brilliant green tourmaline is slightly warm to the touch and exhibits a perceptible luster to the eye. However, when its magic is spent, the gem loses its warmth and luster.
Unlike the Greater Gem of Seeing, the Lesser Gem of Seeing can only disrupt lesser illusion spells, and only when the command word is invoked.

STATISTICS:
  Cast Detect Illusion once/day
  Cast Detect Invisibility once/day
  Cast Clairvoyance five times per day

Not Usable By:
Wizardslayer
~

// Charged Gem of Seeing ------------------------------ 21
COPY ~grand_duke/itm/rqgem03.itm~ ~override/rqgem03.itm~
/* Unidentified name */
SAY NAME1 ~Emerald~
/* Identified name */
SAY NAME2 ~Lesser Divining Gem DIl & Cl~

SAY UNIDENTIFIED_DESC
~Tourmaline is a versatile, semi-transparent gemstone known for its wide range of vibrant colors, including striking blue varieties like indicolite, with a glass-like luster and good durability. Its unique crystal structure and range of hues make it a popular choice for jewelry.~

SAY DESC
~Lesser Divining Gem DIl & Cl
This charged Lesser Divining Gem was originally created by the sorcerer Tverogun, who resided in Daerlun. It was enchanted within four days, as it was seen as a necessary tool for a band of adventurers hired to eliminate the illusionist Mergel, who was the leader of a raiding band threatening Daerlun. Chroniclers record that the band used the gem to dispel weaker illusions cast by Mergel but succumbed to more powerful illusions. Another notable instance in history involved conjurer Temryn, who used the gem against an illusionist and died as a result because the gem was unable to dispel the more powerful illusions. After this second misfortune, the gem greatly lost in value.
Some scholars strongly dispute the fanciful tale about Tverogun creating the gem and point to the standard size of tourmalines compared to other charged divination gems, as well as markings indicating which spells could be cast. all of which suggests an old, forgotten manufacturing guild which specialized in the production of charged divination gems.
When fully charged, the brilliant green tourmaline is slightly warm to the touch and has a perceptible luster. The letters "DIl & Cl" are inscribed at the top of the gem, likely indicating which spells can be cast. The gem when its magic is spent, it loses its warmth and luster. Unlike the greater Gem of Seeing, the Lesser Divining Gem can only disrupt lesser illusion spells and only when the command word is invoked.

STATISTICS:
  Cast Detect Illusion thrice/day
  Cast Clairvoyance once/day~

// Horologium Acidum ------------------------------ 22
COPY ~grand_duke/itm/rqmisc01.itm~ ~override/rqmisc01.itm~
/* Unidentified name */
SAY NAME1 ~Hourglass~
/* Identified name */
SAY NAME2 ~Horologium Acidum~

SAY UNIDENTIFIED_DESC
~This instrument, made of two bulbs of glass joined by a narrow passage, tells time with a portion of sand that falls between the two bulbs. Hour glasses are a common time telling device throughout the Realms.~

SAY DESC
~Horologium Acidum
This bizarre time-measuring device is not used for measuring time at all; in fact, it can be used to unleash a spell. Scholars do not have a sufficient understanding of it, and these creations have generated many competing theories about their origin. Probably the most well-known story is about Lich Ezgurdel, who supposedly used this or similar devices to punish his misbehaving servants or slaves. Another tale suggests that these were created for the Church of Mystra to keep time, but some hapless enchanter stole them and used them as enchanting targets to practice his skills. The least known and least fanciful theory is proposed by scholars from the War Wizards of Cormyr, who point to a now-lost parchment documenting an order from an old manufacturing guild that probably specialized in making charged magical devices.

Whatever the case, this specific hourglass can unleash acid on your enemy once a day.

STATISTICS:
  Special Abilities (once per day): Casts acidic blob of spell power of 4th level targeting a single creature chosen by the user.
  Damage: 8d6 (save vs. wands for half)
  Range: 100 ft
  Area: One creature~

// Horologium Lumine ------------------------------ 23
COPY ~grand_duke/itm/rqmisc02.itm~ ~override/rqmisc02.itm~
/* Unidentified name */
SAY NAME1 ~Hourglass~
/* Identified name */
SAY NAME2 ~Horologium Lumine~

SAY UNIDENTIFIED_DESC
~This instrument, made of two bulbs of glass joined by a narrow passage, tells time with a portion of sand that falls between the two bulbs. Hour glasses are a common time telling device throughout the Realms.~

SAY DESC
~Horologium Lumine
This bizarre time-measuring device is not used for measuring time at all; in fact, it can be used to unleash a spell. Scholars do not have a sufficient understanding of it, and these creations have generated many competing theories about their origin. Probably the most well-known story is about Lich Ezgurdel, who supposedly used this or similar devices to punish his misbehaving servants or slaves. Another tale suggests that these were created for the Church of Mystra to keep time, but some hapless enchanter stole them and used them as enchanting targets to practice his skills. The least known and least fanciful theory is proposed by scholars from the War Wizards of Cormyr, who point to a now-lost parchment documenting an order from an old manufacturing guild that probably specialized in making charged magical devices.

Whatever the case, this specific hourglass can unleash lightning bolt on your enemy once a day.

STATISTICS:
  Special Abilities (once per day): Casts an lightning bolt with spell power of 4th level targeting a single creature chosen by the user.
  Damage: 8d6 (save vs. wands for half)
  Range: 100 ft
  Area: One creature~

// Horologium Frigidum ------------------------------ 24
COPY ~grand_duke/itm/rqmisc03.itm~ ~override/rqmisc03.itm~
/* Unidentified name */
SAY NAME1 ~Hourglass~
/* Identified name */
SAY NAME2 ~Horologium Frigidum~

SAY UNIDENTIFIED_DESC
~This instrument, made of two bulbs of glass joined by a narrow passage, tells time with a portion of sand that falls between the two bulbs. Hour glasses are a common time telling device throughout the Realms.~

SAY DESC
~Horologium Frigidum
This bizarre time-measuring device is not used for measuring time at all; in fact, it can be used to unleash a spell. Scholars do not have a sufficient understanding of it, and these creations have generated many competing theories about their origin. Probably the most well-known story is about Lich Ezgurdel, who supposedly used this or similar devices to punish his misbehaving servants or slaves. Another tale suggests that these were created for the Church of Mystra to keep time, but some hapless enchanter stole them and used them as enchanting targets to practice his skills. The least known and least fanciful theory is proposed by scholars from the War Wizards of Cormyr, who point to a now-lost parchment documenting an order from an old manufacturing guild that probably specialized in making charged magical devices.

Whatever the case, this specific hourglass can unleash cold arrow on your enemy.

STATISTICS:
